Separate the class that does the work from the class that holds the value:

    struct Logger {
      struct Line {
        Logger &amp;log;
        int n;
        void debug(const char *s)
        {log.debug(n,s);}
      };

      Line at(int n) {return {*this,n};}

    private:
      void debug(int n,const char *s)
      {std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Num : &quot;  &lt;&lt; n &lt;&lt; &quot; :: Message : &quot; &lt;&lt; s &lt;&lt; std::endl;}
    };

You can make `Logger` a friend of `Line` to avoid exposing a constructible helper, but anyone can pass anything to `at` anyway.

Note here that `Logger::debug` doesnt use `this`; if thats true in the real case, make it `static` (or not a member function at all) and you can simplify `Line` and avoid a singleton, which is a major win (especially in a multithreaded environment).

